{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "In developing this data set, the researchers asked 4000 human participants to score almost 40,000 words on a scale of 1-5, with 1 meaning abstract and 5 meaning concrete.",
    "Abstract words have \"meanings that cannot be experienced directly but which we know because the meanings can be defined by other words\", while concrete ones are those which one \"can experience directly through one of the five senses\" (Brysbaert et al. 2014).",
    "To calculate the concreteness of our complaints, we tokenized the text from each complaint.",
    "For each token within each text, we obtained the average concreteness score therefor from the Brysbaert et al. (2014) data set.",
    "We used code published by Kleinberg et al. (2019) for this task."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Abstract words have \"meanings that cannot be experienced directly but which we know because the meanings can be defined by other words\", while concrete ones are those which one \"can experience directly through one of the five senses\" (Brysbaert et al. 2014).",
